polyrabies 2024-12-12 05:28 a.m.
To the Honorable Court:
This response is submitted on behalf of my clients, SinisterInfernal and neu_trooper, in relation to the court’s directive to show cause regarding the execution of the search warrant issued for "wertywer2" (hereinafter referred to as the “subject”) on or about December 11th, 2024.
1. Background and Factual Clarifications
On December 12th, 2024, my clients, SinisterInfernal and neu_trooper, acting in their official capacity as Military Police Officers within the Mayflower National Guard, executed the warrant directed to all Military Police Officers within the State.
Upon reviewing the warrant, my clients encountered ambiguity in its phrasing, which led to confusion regarding its precise scope. The warrant directed, in part, that the “SEARCH IS TO INCLUDE INDIVIDUAL'S *IMMEDIATE POSSESSIONS, VEHICLE PRESENT AT THE TIME OF EXECUTION, AND A GREEN CALA JACKALOPE LINKED TO THE INDIVIDUAL.” The inclusion of the term “IMMEDIATE POSSESSIONS”, when read alongside the directive to search the “vehicle present at the time of execution” and “a Green Cala Jackalope linked to the individual,” was inherently vague and open to differing interpretations. My clients understood this language to include all vehicles owned by the subject due to the lack of explicit limiting language within the warrant.
2. Warrant Vagueness and Good Faith Execution
The phrasing of the warrant created great uncertainty, especially in a high-stress operational environment involving the apprehension of an individual suspected of possessing Non-Civilian Grade Weaponary. The ambiguity of the phrase “IMMEDIATE POSSESSIONS” was reasonably interpreted as referring to vehicles which are immediately accessible to the subject which all vehicles in his possession were immediately accessible to the subject through the utilisation of a car spawner, caused my clients to reasonably believe they were authorized to search all vehicles owned by the subject.
polyrabies 2024-12-12 05:28 a.m.
At no point was there any willful disregard or intentional disobedience of the court’s directives. My clients executed their duties in good faith, operating under the belief that their interpretation of the warrant aligned with its intended scope.
3. Seized Items
Despite the confusion, all items and possessions seized during the search were found to be illegal for the suspect to possess, including a functioning taser. This demonstrates that, despite the error, my clients fulfilled their duties to further public safety as Military Police Officers by the recovery of Non Civilian Grade Equipment.
4. Conclusions

Criminal contempt requires willful disobedience of a court order. In this case, the vagueness of the warrant’s language caused reasonable confusion, rather than any deliberate act of defiance. Given the circumstances of the ambiguity and the good faith efforts of my clients, we respectfully request that the court find no basis for criminal contempt.
We further request that the court acknowledge the need for greater precision in the drafting of warrants to prevent such issues in the future.

Thank you.
POLYRABIES
polyrabies 2024-12-12 08:15 a.m.

Awesome 2024-12-12 08:55 a.m.
The good-faith exception is a limit on the exclusionary rule of the Fourth Amendment and has nothing to do with civil or criminal contempt; in any case, it would not apply, given the Defendants’ search was clearly beyond the scope of the warrant. United States v. Leon, 468 U.S. 897, 921–22 (1984).

The search, in no uncertain terms, was to be performed “WITHIN THE PROVIDED PARAMETERS,” and was to include, exclusively, “INDIVIDUAL'S IMMEDIATE POSSESSIONS, VEHICLE PRESENT AT THE TIME OF EXECUTION, AND A GREEN CALA JACKALOPE LINKED TO THE INDIVIDUAL.” The Defendants’ argument that “immediate possessions” encompasses all vehicles is, frankly, specious; “immediate possessions” is followed soon thereafter by “vehicle present at the time of execution” and “a [specific vehicle] linked to the individual.” The Defendants’ purported mistake of fact was, thus, prima facie wholly unreasonable.

The Court will thus proceed with a hearing.
